04839nam a22005535i 9780822394167DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223941677 a10.1515/97808223941672doi  a(DE-B1597)552337  a(OCoLC)757836208  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1995.9.D6 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a070.1800aUseful Cinema /cHaidee Wasson, Charles R. Acland. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (398 p.) :b56 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Utility and Cinema -- t"What a Power for Education!": The Cinema and Sites of Learning in the 1930s -- t"We Can See Ourselves as Others See Us": Women Workers and Western Union's Training Films in the 1920s -- tHollywood's Educators: Mark May and Teaching Film Custodians -- tUnesco, Film, and Education: Mediating Postwar Paradigms of Communication -- tHealth Films, Cold War, and the Production of Patriotic Audiences: The Body Fights Bacteria (1948) -- tProjecting the Promise of 16mm, 1935-45 -- tA History Long Overdue: The Public Library and Motion Pictures -- tBig, Fast Museums / Small, Slow Movies: Film, Scale, and the Art Museum -- tPastoral Exhibition: The YMCA Motion Picture Bureau and the Transition to 16mm, 1928-39 -- t"A Moving Picture of the Heavens": The Planetarium Space Show as Useful Cinema -- tDouble Vision: World War II, Racial Uplift, and the All- American Newsreel's Pedagogical Address -- tMechanical Craftsmanship: Amateurs Making Practical Films -- tExperimental Film as Useless Cinema -- tFilmography -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy exploring the use of film in mid-twentieth-century institutions, including libraries, museums, classrooms, and professional organizations, the essays in Useful Cinema show how moving images became an ordinary feature of American life. In venues such as factories and community halls, people encountered industrial, educational, training, advertising, and other types of "useful cinema." Screening these films transformed unlikely spaces, conveyed ideas, and produced subjects in the service of public and private aims. Such functional motion pictures helped to shape common sense about cinema's place in contemporary life. Whether measured in terms of the number of films shown, the size of audiences, or the economic activity generated, the "non-theatrical sector" was a substantial and enduring parallel to the more spectacular realm of commercial film. In Useful Cinema, scholars examine organizations such as UNESCO, the YMCA, the Amateur Cinema League, and the Metropolitan Museum of Art. They also consider film exhibition sites in schools, businesses, and industries. As they expand understanding of this other American cinema, the contributors challenge preconceived notions about what cinema is.Contributors. Charles R. Acland, Joseph Clark, Zoë Druick, Ronald Walter Greene, Alison Griffiths, Stephen Groening, Jennifer Horne, Kirsten Ostherr, Eric Smoodin, Charles Tepperman, Gregory A. Waller, Haidee Wasson. Michael Zryd  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aDocumentary filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aNonfiction filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAcland, Charles R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWasson, Haidee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394167zCo